sentence: Crude dips on supply data , U.S. monetary policy uncertainty .

Investing.com - U.S. crude oil prices edged lower on Wednesday on lackluster supply data as well as due to uncertainty over when Federal Reserve monetary stimulus programs may taper and eventually end .

Federal Reserve stimulus programs such as monthly bond purchases push down interest rates to drive recovery , weakening the greenback in the process and making oil an attractive buy in dollar-denominated commodities exchanges .
Talk of an end to stimulus tends to have the reverse effect .
On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light sweet crude futures for delivery in September traded at USD104 .92 a barrel during U.S. trading , down 0.36 % .
The September contract settled down 1.18 % at USD105 .30 a barrel on Tuesday .

The U.S. Energy Information Administration said in its weekly report earlier Wednesday that U.S. crude oil inventories fell by 1.3 million barrels in the week ending August 2 , roughly in line with expectations for a decline of 1.2 million barrels .
Total U.S. crude oil inventories stood at 363.3 million barrels as of last week .
The report also showed that total motor gasoline inventories increased by 135,000 barrels , defying expectations for a decline of 763,000 barrels .
Elsewhere , uncertainty over the fate of Federal Reserve stimulus measures kept prices lower .

Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago President Charles Evans , a noted policy dove , said the U.S. central bank could begin tapering its USD85 billion bond-buying program later this year if the economy improves .

Other monetary authorities including Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas President Richard Fisher and Atlanta Fed Chief Atlanta Fed president Dennis Lockhart made similar comments , which softened oil prices .
Still , until the Federal Reserve announces such plans to taper , monthly bond purchases will stay in place and support oil , though ongoing uncertainty softened the commodity .
Elsewhere , on the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for September delivery were down 0.46 % at USD107 .69 a barrel , up USD2 .77 from its U.S. counterpart .
